The British thought that the German attack on 30 April, was an attempted surprise, by discharging the gas in an unfavourable high wind, to allow troops to follow up without the risk of being gassed. When the British saw that the German infantry were without masks, they unmasked too. The effect of the gas was similar to that of the phosgene discharge of 19 December 1915 but in a more concentrated form, in which a short exposure to the gas was fatal. The course of the cloud could be seen by the staining of grass and vegetation as far as Bailleul, where shoots and leaves withered; cattle died {{convert|2|mi|km}} to the north-east. It was concluded that the dangerous concentration of gas extended for {{convert|9000|–|10000|yd|m}} from the point of discharge. It was also found that the new box respirator worn by some machine-gunners gave good protection.{{sfn|Edmonds|1993|p=202}}  Defensive artillery-fire had defeated most of the German infantry attacks and many German trench mortars were destroyed by the fire of [[BL 8-inch howitzer Mk I–V|8-inch]] and [[BL 9.2-inch howitzer|9.2-inch]] [[howitzer]]s but relatively little artillery-fire was devoted to counter-battery bombardments.{{sfn|Farndale|1986|p=136}}

===Casualties===
On 30 April, there were {{nowrap|562 British}} gas casualties, of whom {{nowrap|89 were}} fatal. In the 3rd Division {{nowrap|69 gassings}} were reported and in the 24th Division {{nowrap|338 losses}} to gas were recorded. Non-gas casualties amounted to {{nowrap|103 in}} the 3rd Division and {{nowrap|209 in}} the 24th Division. The difference in the number of casualties, was explained by four battalions and working parties being in the path of the gas on the 24th Division front, some of whom did not receive the warnings and only one 3rd Division battalion, which was also fortunate that the gas moved south-west, away from the rear areas of the division. German reports mention only that a senior officer was wounded.{{sfn|Edmonds|1993|pp=203, 205}} The gas discharge on 17 June, caused {{nowrap|562 British}} casualties, of which {{nowrap|95 were}} fatal. The 72nd Brigade gas casualties were {{nowrap|348, most}} incurred by the 1st North Staffs, the 73rd Brigade had {{nowrap|70 gas}} casualties out of {{nowrap|137 losses}} and the 17th Brigade had {{nowrap|24 gas}} casualties among {{nowrap|48}} losses.{{sfn|Edmonds|1993|p=204}}

===Medical narrative===

[[File:German cloud gas attack at Wulverghem with locations of aid posts and advanced dressing stations.png|thumb|{{center|German cloud gas attack at Wulverghem, with locations of aid posts and advanced dressing stations}}]]
From north to south, the units mainly affected the 3rd Division in the 76th Brigade were the 10th [[Royal Welch Fusiliers]] (10th RWF) and in the 72nd Brigade, 24th Division, the 1st North Staffs, 8th Queen's and the 2nd [[Prince of Wales's Leinster Regiment (Royal Canadians)|Leinsters]] and the 13th [[Middlesex Regiment|Middlesex]] of the 73rd Brigade. The gas release began at {{nowrap|12:35 a.m.}} on a front of {{convert|3500|yd|m}}, from Spanbroekmolen to La Petite Douvre Farm, except for two small sectors. In the north the flow of gas was continuous for about ten minutes and farther south the gas came in two waves, over {{nowrap|30–40 minutes.}} As soon as the gas cloud drifted German attacks began, mainly at points where no gas had been released. Shell or trench mortar bombs with [[chloromethyl chloroformate]] were used against the front line and some lacrymatory "T" shells were fired on the British support lines, with no effect. The gas moved east-north-east at {{convert|9|–|12|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} over Wulverghem, Neuve Eglise and Bailleul. Gas concentration on the flanks of the cloud declined rapidly but at Bailleul, {{convert|11000|yd|m}} back from the front line, coughing and vomiting occurred in some cases of people caught the open. Closing windows and doors kept most of the gas out of buildings. On high ground near Neuve Eglise, the concentration was low but was high on Ravelsberg Ridge to the west.{{sfn|MacPherson|1923|pp=278–279}}

Vegetation was turned yellow as far back as {{nowrap|1200|yd|m}} from the front line. Many rats in the trenches were killed and eleven cows, {{nowrap|23 calves,}} a horse, one pig and {{nowrap|15 hens}} were killed in fields; other cattle and pigs showed signs of gas poisoning. A potentially lethal concentration for an unmasked person extended for {{convert|9000|–|10000|yd|m}} from the discharge point and about {{nowrap|14,000 troops}} donned gas helmets during the attack, including many on the outskirts of the cloud, who wore helmets as a precaution. Troops in the front line received little warning before the gas arrived. In places the cloud was seen to rise from the German trenches as a white mist and hissing was audible at some points but was drowned by rifle and machine-gun fire elsewhere. In the north, the opposing trenches were {{convert|40|yd|m}} apart and the gas cloud arrived in seconds, highly concentrated. The standard anti-gas equipment of "PH" helmets and "box respirators" for machine-gunners, signallers and some artillery personnel had been issued. The box respirator was a great success, because the face piece could be fitted quicker than the "PH" helmet.{{sfn|MacPherson|1923|p=279}}

[[File:British soldier in a P or PH helmet.jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|{{center|British soldier demonstrates a P or PH helmet}}]]
In the 72nd Brigade, helmets were carried in protective satchels but in the 76th Brigade, helmets were removed before the attack and worn on the head, as recently advised. A large number of gas casualties occurred despite warnings and having been alerted for the attack; some groups received late warnings or underestimated the danger and a small number were caught asleep. The speed and concentration of the cloud meant that hesitation or fumbling with the mask resulted in poisoning. Most casualties occurred in the front line in trenches close to the German lines.{{sfn|MacPherson|1923|pp=279–280}} Gas may have been strong enough to penetrate helmets in trenches nearest to the gas discharge, yet the 10th RWF had only {{nowrap|41 gas}} casualties, five casualties among engineers and five among trench mortar crews, compared with {{nowrap|112 casualties}} in the 1st North Staffs and {{nowrap|122 among}} the 8th Queen's in the 72nd Brigade. The 10th RWF had followed advice to keep the helmet ready and the gas blew sideways, missing the area further back. Casualty returns from battalions, field ambulances and casualty clearing stations, gave total gas casualties as {{nowrap|512, including}} casualties in infantry battalions on the flanks and in reserve and among divisional and corps troops. The five battalions in the line (excluding machine-gun, R.E., tunnelling companies and trench mortar crews) had {{nowrap|371 gas}} casualties, {{nowrap|73 percent of}} the total.{{sfn|MacPherson|1923|p=281}}

The regimental aid post of the 10th RWF was about {{convert|600|yd|m}} back from the front line and No. 7 Field Ambulance of the 3rd Division was at Locre Hospice. An advanced dressing station was at Lindenhoek and took most of its casualties from the 10th RWF. Most casualties from the 72nd and 73rd Brigades passed through No. 73 Field Ambulance of the 24th Division, whose main dressing station was at Dranoutre, with an advanced dressing station in a farm near Wulverghem, about {{convert|2000|yd|m}} from the front line, in the path of the gas. Entrances to the dressing station had anti-gas curtains and the gas failed to penetrate, the occupants carrying on without helmets. No. 74 Field Ambulance in the 24th Division area, had an advanced dressing station at Hyde Park Corner on the north edge of Ploegsteert Wood, a main dressing station to the south-west at Le Romarin and had only a few casualties. The aid post of the 1st North Staffs was set on fire early in the attack by shell fire and burnt out.{{sfn|MacPherson|1923|p=281}}

Regimental aid posts were cleared of the first rush of cases by {{nowrap|10:00 a.m.,}} though minor gas casualties trickled in for another {{nowrap|24 hours.}} For a few days, small numbers of soldiers reported with symptoms of bronchitis, which were attributed to the gas. Casualties were evacuated as soon as possible from the aid posts to the field ambulances, severe cases first albeit slowly, because all troops suffering from the gas were treated as lying cases and carried by hand or on wheeled stretchers. Cases admitted at Lindenhoek, were evacuated by a thirty-minute car journey, to the main station at Locre Hospice. Some casualties arrived at Locre within three hours of the gas attack and all cases were detained for several hours, until some improvement was seen. Lighter cases were sent on to casualty clearing stations first and some of the worst cases were retained for treatment, to spare them the effects of another journey, as the unit had good accommodation.{{sfn|MacPherson|1923|p=281}}

[[File:British soldier in a Small Box respirator.jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|{{center|British soldier demonstrates a small box respirator}}]]
Most casualties passed through the advanced dressing station near Wulverghem, to the main dressing station of No. 73 Field Ambulance at Dranoutre. There was little accommodation there for severe casualties, who were evacuated as soon as possible to the casualty clearing stations in Bailleul. Severe casualties went first and by noon on 30 April, {{nowrap|143 gas}} casualties had been admitted at Dranoutre, {{nowrap|176 more}} in the next {{nowrap|24 hours,}} eleven in the following {{nowrap|24 hours,}} twelve in the next {{nowrap|24 hours}} and ten more in the next four days. No. 1 Canadian Casualty Clearing Station at Bailleul, admitted casualties from about {{nowrap|4:00 a.m.}} on 30 April and by {{nowrap|8:30 a.m.}} had taken {{nowrap|72 cases.}} No. 8 Casualty Clearing Station at Bailleul began to take casualties and by {{nowrap|12:30 a.m.}} on 1 May, was full with {{nowrap|321 gas}} casualties; later arrivals went on to No. 2 Casualty Clearing Station at Bailleul, which admitted {{nowrap|81 cases.}}{{sfn|MacPherson|1923|p=282}}

The troops worst affected, had intense cyanosis and frothy exudation from the mouth and nose; some of the severe casualties who reached casualty clearing stations, had a pallor and collapse associated with phosgene poisoning. In a few cases cyanosis gave place to pallor before the victim died. The troops who died rapidly in the front line, about ninety minutes after the beginning of the attack, showed deep cyanosis and copious frothing, with paroxysmal coughing prominent in the early stages. The clinical evidence suggested that the gas cloud contained a low proportion of phosgene to chlorine. About twenty civilians were affected by the gas, though none severely, as they had been instructed in gas precautions and had been issued with respirators. The civilians had also protected themselves by closing windows and doors and by filling cracks with wet cloths; many also wore anti-gas helmets indoors.{{sfn|MacPherson|1923|p=282}}

